<DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; FESTIVAL; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  FIREWORKS will light up the sky all over the Bay Area next week. Here are
details on the main displays.;    (star) Downtown San Jose: From July 4 to 7,
the San Jose America Festival takes over Guadalupe River Park with a lineup of
free performances, a food fair, an arts show and a children's festival.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHERE TO KEEP AN EYE ON THE SKY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  (box) San Jose celebrates with a new festival, Page 28
EVENTS  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The America Festival incorporates five downtown events -- Kidland, a
playground/project area for children; the Great Taste, a food and music fair;
the Multicultural Arts Showcase; Tapestry in Talent, the 16-year-old art fair
(July 6-7); and the Independence Day Fireworks Sky Concert.;    The fireworks
will be launched over Guadalupe River Park starting between 9:20 and 9:30 p.m.
The 20-minute show is choreographed with lights and sound and has its own
score and text. Playwright and director Luis Valdez will deliver the oratory,
and the Fabulous Drifters will start the show with "America the Beautiful.";  
 (star) Great America: The Santa Clara amusement park will be open 10 a.m. to
11 p.m. Paul Revere and the Raiders perform at 4 and 8:30 p.m., and the
fireworks show begins at 9:30 p.m.;    Many people head for Great America in
hopes of finding a spot outside the park to watch the fireworks for free. Keep
in mind that many businesses surrounding Great America reserve their parking
lots for their employees on Independence Day.;    Santa Clara City police plan
to divert traffic on streets near Great America, and the California Highway
Patrol says officers will tow cars that stop along Highway 101. (408)
988-1776.;    (star) San Jose Giants: The baseball club features fireworks
after the game on Wednesday and Thursday nights. The games start at 7:15 p.m.
at Municipal Stadium, Tenth and Alma streets, San Jose. Admission is $5, $3
for seniors and children. (408) 297-1435.;    (star) Mirassou Winery:
Wine-tasting begins at 7 p.m. Thursday, followed by a pops concert with the
Nova Vista Symphony and fireworks at the winery, 3000 Aborn Road, San Jose.
Tickets, $20, are available at the Mirassou Tasting Room and at BASS/TM
outlets only. (408) 274-4000.;    (star) Milpitas: The Fourth of July begins
at 8:30 a.m. in Milpitas with 5- and 10-kilometer runs at the city's sports
complex, 1325 E. Calaveras Blvd. Then it's fun in adjacent Cardoza Park from 9
a.m. to 4 p.m. The fireworks are launched from the Main Street fire station,;
25 W. Curtis St., at 9:30 p.m.;    (star) Aromas: Graniterock Company of
Watsonville is sponsoring a Fourth of July concert of American pop music,
featuring the Santa Cruz County Symphony, Monterey County Symphony and the
Watsonville Band, in its A.R. Wilson Quarry in the tiny Santa Cruz County town
of Aromas. The concert, which will benefit the United Way of San Benito County
and the participating musical groups, will be followed by fireworks. Doors
open at 4:30 p.m. at the quarry. Tickets are $20, $10 for children 3-12 and
free for children under 3. No tickets will be sold at the door. (800)
696-4515.;    (star) Mountain View: Moffett Field holds a public celebration
from 9 to 11 a.m. Thursday to honor the U.S. military. Gates open at 8 a.m.;  
 The San Francisco Symphony will play a pops concert followed by fireworks at
Shoreline Amphitheater in Mountain View. Doors open at 5 p.m. and the concert
begins at 8 p.m. Tickets are $15.50-$22.50. (415) 967-4040.;    (star) Redwood
City: It all starts with a pancake breakfast at 7:30 a.m. at 814 Hamilton
Ave., downtown Redwood City. A fun run follows at 9:15 a.m., a parade begins
at 10:30 a.m. and the festival, featuring crafts, games and entertainment,
runs 1-5 p.m. Fireworks, shot over the bay from South Shore in Redwood City,
start at 9:30 p.m. (415) 365-1825.;    (star) San Francisco: The celebration
at Crissy Field features entertainment on two stages, food concessions and
fireworks. Entertainment begins at 2 p.m., and the evening ceremonies begin at
8:25 p.m. San Francisco Muni runs extra buses. Bus information: (415)
673-MUNI; festival information: (415) 556-0671.;    (star) Alameda County
Fair: Pat Boone performs at 6 and 8 p.m. in the amphitheater and fireworks
begin about 9:15 p.m. The fair, at 4501 Pleasanton Ave., Pleasanton, is open
10 a.m. to 10 p.m. Admission is $6, $3 for seniors, $1 for children 6 to 12
and free for children under 6. (415) 846-2881.;    (star) Concord: The Concord
Pavilion presents fireworks after shows Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday
nights. The Diablo Symphony Pops perform Tuesday at 8 p.m., the Preservation
Hall Jazz Band performs Wednesday at 8 p.m., and the California Symphony
performs Thursday at 8 p.m. Tickets are $17 reserved and $15 for lawn seating
through BASS/TM outlets.  </TEXT>
